Activity 2

We use the famous titanic dataset1 for this question.

Data import

We start off by importing data.

Code 
titanic = read.csv("titanic.csv")

titanic dataset has 891 observations and 12 variables.

Overview of the data

Note

summary function doesnât show meaningful results for categorical variables.

Categorical variables in titanic data are Name, Sex, Ticket, Cabin, and Embarked. (There are probably more categorical variables such as Survived, but we just follow the data format as it is.)

Categorical variables

Code 
# Contingency table for sex
table(titanic$Sex)

female   male 
   314    577
Code 
# Contingency table for sex
table(titanic$Embarked)

      C   Q   S 
  2 168  77 644

Variable Emarked denotes the port of embarkation. C stands for Cherbourg, Q for Queenstown, and S for Southampton.

Data Visualizations

Code 
ggplot(aes(x = Age), data = titanic) +
   geom_boxplot() +
   theme_minimal()
Note

We use \(\sqrt{\text{Fare}}\) for the plot as it is highly skewed.

Code 
titanic$Survived = as.factor(titanic$Survived)

ggplot(aes(x = Age, y = sqrt(Fare), color = Survived), data = titanic) +
   geom_point() +
   theme_minimal()
